<div class=3D"file-macro-container include4confluence include4confluence-co=
ntent">
<div class=3D"include4confluence-panel panel" id=3D"include4confluence-bord=
er">
<div class=3D"include4confluence-panel-content-container ">
<div id=3D"include4confluence-markdown" class=3D"include4confluence-panel-c=
ontent">
<h3 id=3D"user-content-commands">Commands</h3>
<p>Mesh Developer Tools provides a way to create and work with a Mesh Compo=
nent. Mesh Developer tools commands can be executed from any Command Prompt=
 or Git Bash terminal.</p>
<p><em><strong>Note</strong></em>: <em>All mesh commands for a component mu=
st be executed from within the component git repository</em></p>
<p>Mesh Developer Tools has the following set of commands and options that =
developers can run:</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-global-options">Global Options:</h4>
<p>These are standard global options that can be used with any mesh command=
:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>--version</strong> Show the version and exit.</li>
<li><strong>-h</strong>, <strong>--help</strong> Show this message and exit=
.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-common-command-options">Common Command Options:</h4>
<p>Most mesh commands support these common options that must be placed <str=
ong>after</strong> the command name:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>-v</strong>, <strong>--verbose</strong> Enable verbose loggi=
ng (can be used multiple times for increased verbosity). This option sets t=
he logging level automatically when used.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>mesh deploy --verbose --build_number 123<=
/code> or <code>mesh deploy -vv --build_number 123</code> (extra verbose)</=
li>
</ul></li>
<li><p><strong>-q</strong>, <strong>--quiet</strong> Skip yes/no confirmati=
on prompts (assumes default response). This affects commands like deploy, u=
ndeploy, secrets, gencode, sync apply, and others that ask for yes/no confi=
rmation. Other interactive prompts (user input, selections) are not affecte=
d.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Usage:</strong> <code>mesh deploy --quiet --build_number 123</c=
ode></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>Both options work automatically without requiring function parameters an=
d are available on most mesh commands.</p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-list-of-commands">List of commands:</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#incubate">incubate</a></strong> Initialise a Incuba=
tor Component Repository for the Mesh Platform</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#gencode">gencode</a></strong> Generate skeleton cod=
e using the gencode utilities</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#gencode">genclient-contract</a></strong> Generate t=
he client contract for openapi.yaml</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#enable">enable</a></strong> Enable capabilities for=
 the Mesh Platform</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#validate">validate</a></strong> Validate configurat=
ion files in the component</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#run">run</a></strong> Run component locally (using =
mvn or npm for java or node components respectively)</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#secrets">secrets</a></strong> Manage encryption of =
the secrets in your repository</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#build">build</a></strong> Trigger custom build</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#deploy">deploy</a></strong> Deploy the component</l=
i>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#undeploy">undeploy</a></strong> Undeploy the compon=
ent from a virtual swimlane</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#status">status</a></strong> Show status of current =
component</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#update">update</a></strong> Update Mesh Developer T=
ools to the latest version</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#swimlane">swimlane</a></strong> Enrol or unenrol a =
virtual swimlane from the component repository</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#prodfix">prodfix</a></strong> Create a prodfix bran=
ch for non-trunk development</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync">sync</a></strong> Manage deployment synchroni=
zation manifests across environments=20
<ul>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_import">sync import</a></strong> Import curren=
t deployment state into a sync manifest</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_resolve">sync resolve</a></strong> Resolve 'la=
test' versions to actual deployed versions</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_plan">sync plan</a></strong> Show what changes=
 would be made by applying a manifest</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_apply">sync apply</a></strong> Apply a sync ma=
nifest to deploy/undeploy components</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_release">sync release</a></strong> Create a pr=
od1 change request from a sync manifest</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#sync_validate">sync validate</a></strong> Validate =
a sync manifest against the schema</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#config">config</a></strong> Manage mesh configurati=
on file=20
<ul>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#config_show">config show</a></strong> Display curre=
nt configuration settings</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#config_set">config set</a></strong> Set a configura=
tion value</li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#config_init">config init</a></strong> Create a defa=
ult configuration file</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong><a href=3D"#connect">connect</a></strong> Open a component page=
 in Mesh Connect</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-incubate">incubate<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The incubate command is used to initialise an Incubator Component Reposi=
tory(earlier known as 'Certification') for the Mesh Platform. All arguments=
 are optional. A prompt will be presented to request any required values th=
at have not been supplied, or to correct any supplied values that are not v=
alid.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/Incubator+=
Environment" rel=3D"nofollow">Incubator</a> components can be created eithe=
r by not entering a name and following the prompts to select the incubator =
domain, or by specifying a component name that includes a domain name of "<=
strong>incubator-[staff id]</strong>".</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage">Usage</h4>
<p>The incubator command takes in a number of optional arguments.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-n, --name</td>
<td>Component name. Must conform to the <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.w=
estpac.com.au/display/MESH/Naming+Standards" rel=3D"nofollow">Mesh naming s=
tandards</a>.</td>
<td>-p wdp-layer-domain-subdomain-subdomain-name-v1-api</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-valid-typecontractlanguage-combinations">VALID TYPE/=
CONTRACT/LANGUAGE COMBINATIONS</h5>
<p>mesh incubate -n (Defaults with: -c api -a rest -i java)</p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples">EXAMPLES</h5>
<p><code>mesh incubate</code> (Will be prompted for all options)</p>
<p><code>mesh incubate -n wdp-cap-incubator-l012345-test-v1-api</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-enable">enable<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The enable command is used to overlay a new capability onto the existing=
 api/listener. Make sure you execute this command from within the component=
 repository.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-1">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh enable [-a &lt;capability&gt;]
</code></pre>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-a, --capability</td>
<td>(Optional) Overlay capability to the existing api/listener</td>
<td>-a kafkaProducer</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-gencode">gencode<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The gencode command is used to generate the source code along with the h=
ealthcheck from the swagger.yaml for the Mesh API's which have implementati=
on type as java or node. Make sure you execute this command from within the=
 component repository. By default, gencode supports Java 11, Tomcat 9. All =
related dependencies will be added to generated POM.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-2">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh gencode [-i &lt;implementation&gt;]
</code></pre>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-i, --implementation</td>
<td>Implementation (supported types are 'jaxrs' (default) or 'spring' for j=
avaweb and 'web' (default) or 'webflux' for springboot)</td>
<td>-i spring</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/How+to+upg=
rade+APIs+to+Tomcat9" rel=3D"nofollow">Click Here</a></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-genclient-contract">genclient-contract<a rel=3D"nofo=
llow"></a></h3>
<p>This command generates the client contract for your openapi.yaml, which =
includes the Mesh platform headers. It will be generated from the most rece=
nt build, not your local copy of the contract.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-3">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh genclient-contract =20
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-run">run<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The run command is used to execute the API on your local machine and val=
idate the implementation. You can also check the healthcheck to make sure y=
our API is healthy on your local environment.</p>
<p>Make sure you execute this command from within the component repository.=
</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-4">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh run [-m &lt;True&gt;]
</code></pre>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-m, --mocks_enabled</td>
<td>(Optional) Run the api instance connecting to mockoon localhost in 3010=
 port</td>
<td>-m True</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-secrets">secrets<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The secrets command is used to encrypt all the secrets of your component=
. It will use the platform keys to encrypt your secrets and secrets will be=
 made available in the container inside your secrets directory.</p>
<p>Refer the <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/=
How+to+Encrypt+Secrets+Before+Uploading+Files+to+Bitbucket" rel=3D"nofollow=
">how to guide</a> for the detailed steps.</p>
<p>Make sure you execute this command from within the component repository.=
</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-5">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh secrets
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-build">build<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The build command is used to trigger a custom build of your component. I=
t is only valid for "api" and "listener" components. If no revision is spec=
ified then the latest code from the current branch will be used.</p>
<p>Make sure you execute this command from within the component repository.=
</p>
<p>For incubator projects only - Components with a remote repository in the=
 Bitbucket incubator project (wdpcert) will have their latest codebase on m=
aster built and deployed to the incubator environment. No command line argu=
ments are required.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-6">Usage</h4>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-n, --component_name</td>
<td>Component Name (defaults to component checked out in current directory)=
</td>
<td>-n exp-dream-core-v1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-t, --component_type</td>
<td>Component Type (will infer from name if not provided, and prompt if amb=
iguous)</td>
<td>-t api</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-b, --revision</td>
<td>Branch, tag or commit id for build (defaults to upstream of current bra=
nch)</td>
<td>-b feature/new-thing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-d, --target</td>
<td>Deploy target (environment or swimlane) to sequentially deploy to (allo=
ws multiple)</td>
<td>-t dev1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples-1">EXAMPLES</h5>
<p>Build feature branch of provided component</p>
<p><code>mesh build --component_name exp-dream-core-v1 -component_type api =
--revision feature/new</code></p>
<p>Build default branch of provided component with implicit type</p>
<p><code>mesh build --component_name exp-dream-core-v1</code></p>
<p>Build default branch of current component</p>
<p><code>mesh build</code></p>
<p>Build default branch of current component and deploy to multiple environ=
ments</p>
<p><code>mesh build --target dev1 --target sit1 --target dev-swimlane</code=
></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-deploy">deploy<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The deploy command is used to deploy your component to a target environm=
ent or swimlane.</p>
<p>This command must be executed from within the repository corresponding t=
o the component that will be deployed.</p>
<p>The build number must be specified along with an optional config build n=
umber and/or secrets build number. The deployment target (environment or sw=
imlane) must also be specified.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-7">Usage</h4>
<p>The deploy command takes in a number of arguments (only required for non=
 incubator deployments).</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-n, --component_name</td>
<td>Component Name (defaults to component checked out in current directory)=
</td>
<td>-n exp-dream-core-v1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-t, --component_type</td>
<td>Component Type (will infer from name if not provided, and prompt if amb=
iguous)</td>
<td>-t api</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-b, --build_number</td>
<td>Component build number</td>
<td>-b 10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-c, --config_version</td>
<td>Config build number (default is component build number)</td>
<td>-c 10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-p, --secret_version</td>
<td>Secrets build number (default is component build number)</td>
<td>-p 10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-e, --environment</td>
<td>Target environment (required if you don't specify a swimlane)</td>
<td>-e dev1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-d, --target</td>
<td>Deploy target (environment or swimlane) to sequentially deploy to (allo=
ws multiple)</td>
<td>-t dev1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-s, --swimlane</td>
<td>Target swimlane (required if you don't specify an environment)</td>
<td>-s sit-swimlane</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples-2">EXAMPLES</h5>
<p>Deploy build number 10 of provided component to sit1</p>
<p><code>mesh deploy --component_name exp-dream-core-v1 -component_type api=
 --build_number 10 --environment sit1</code></p>
<p>Deploy build number 10 of provided component to dev-swimlane1 with impli=
cit type</p>
<p><code>mesh deploy --component_name exp-dream-core-v1 --build_number 10 -=
-swimlane dev-swimlane1</code></p>
<p>Deploy build number 10 of current component with config and secrets from=
 build 11 to uat1</p>
<p><code>mesh deploy --build_number 10 --config_version 11 --secret_version=
 11 --environment uat1</code></p>
<p>Deploy build number 10 of current component with config and secrets from=
 build 11 to sit1, uat1 and sit-test1 swimlane</p>
<p><code>mesh deploy --build_number 10 --config_version 11 --secret_version=
 11 --target sit1 --target uat1 --target sit-test1</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-undeploy">undeploy<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The undeploy command is used to undeploy an api component from a virtual=
 swimlane.</p>
<p>This command must be executed from within the repository corresponding t=
o the component that will be undeployed.</p>
<p>Undeploy is not applicable for proxy components. The command cannot be u=
sed to undeploy a component from a default (non-swimlane) environment.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-8">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh undeploy -s &lt;target swimlane name&gt;
</code></pre>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-s, --swimlane</td>
<td>Target swimlane</td>
<td>-s sit-swimlane</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-status">status<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>Display status information about current component</p>
<p>Make sure you execute this command from within the component repository.=
</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-9">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh status
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-validate">validate<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The validate command validates a yaml against a given schema or default =
schema. Run validate from within component repository to validate the yaml =
files associated with the component.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-10">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh validate
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-swimlane">swimlane<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The swimlane command enrols or enrols a virtual swimlane to/from a compo=
nent repository.</p>
<p>Virtual swimlanes allow multiple instances of a Mesh component to be dep=
loyed independently and in parallel within a single environment.</p>
<p>The swimlanes for a component are stored in the resources.yaml file in t=
he master branch of a component repository.</p>
<p>The swimlane name must be in the following format: (eng|dev|sit|uat)-&lt=
;name&gt;. The name is alphanumeric lower-case only, starts with alpha and =
minimum of 3 characters and maximum of 8 characters. The name cannot be nam=
ed as 'default' as this is a reserved keyword. E.g. dev-john1</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-11">Usage</h4>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-e, --enrol</td>
<td>Enrol in selected swimlane</td>
<td>--enrol</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-u, --unenrol</td>
<td>Unenrol in selected swimlane</td>
<td>--unenrol</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-n, --name</td>
<td>The swimlane name in the format -</td>
<td>-n sit-swimlane</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-valid-commands">VALID COMMANDS:</h5>
<pre><code>mesh swimlane --enrol
mesh swimlane --enrol --name &lt;swimlane name&gt;
mesh swimlane --unenrol
mesh swimlane --unenrol --name &lt;swimlane name&gt;
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples-3">EXAMPLES:</h5>
<pre><code>mesh swimlane --enrol
mesh swimlane --enrol --name dev-john1
mesh swimlane --unenrol
mesh swimlane --unenrol --name sit-bob1
</code></pre>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-examples-4">EXAMPLES:</h4>
<pre><code>mesh incubate
mesh swimlane
mesh build
mesh deploy
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-prodfix">prodfix<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The prodfix command is used to create a prodfix branch for non-trunk dev=
elopment.</p>
<p>This command may be executed from within the repository corresponding to=
 the component that requires the prodfix branch to be created, or the compo=
nent can be selected using the --component_name, --component_type or --repo=
_uri options.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-12">Usage</h4>
<p>The prodfix command takes in a number of arguments. More detailed inform=
ation on the usage of this command can be found here: More detailed instruc=
tions and prerequisites for using swimlanes can be found here: <a href=3D"h=
ttps://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/How+to+guide+on+Non+Trunk=
+Development" rel=3D"nofollow">https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/displa=
y/MESH/How+to+guide+on+Non+Trunk+Development</a></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-n, --component_name</td>
<td>Component Name (defaults to component checked out in current directory)=
</td>
<td>-n exp-dream-core-v1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-t, --component_type</td>
<td>Component Type (will infer from name if not provided, and prompt if amb=
iguous)</td>
<td>-t api</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-b, --build_number</td>
<td>Component build number from which we you want to cut-off your prodfix b=
ranch</td>
<td>-b 10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-bn, --branch_name</td>
<td>Prodfix branch name to be created</td>
<td>-bn fix-problem</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-r, --repo_uri</td>
<td>Repository uri of the component either with ssh or https</td>
<td>-r {repo-url}</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-e, --environment</td>
<td>Environment from which you want to cut-off your prodfix branch. If envi=
ronment is not provided , the command takes prod1 as default environment fo=
r prodfix branch cut-off</td>
<td>-e uat1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-valid-commands-1">VALID COMMANDS:</h5>
<pre><code>mesh prodfix
mesh prodfix -bn fix-problem-in-uat -e uat1
mesh prodfix -b 256
mesh prodfix -b 256 -bn fix-problem
mesh prodfix -bn fix-new-problem
mesh prodfix -bn fix-new-problem -r {repo-url}
mesh prodfix -bn fix-new-problem -r {repo-url} -b 256
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples-5">EXAMPLES</h5>
<p>Create prodfix branch using build number 10 of provided component</p>
<p><code>mesh prodfix --component_name exp-dream-core-v1 --component_type a=
pi --build_number 10 </code></p>
<p>Create prodfix to fix a problem that has been found on svp1 and cutting-=
of from the latest deploy on that environment</p>
<p><code>mesh deploy -e svp1 -bn fix-svp-problem</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-sync">sync<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The sync command provides deployment synchronization functionality to ma=
nage manifests describing desired deployment states across environments. Th=
is is useful for coordinated deployments across multiple components and env=
ironments.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-13">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh sync &lt;subcommand&gt; [options]
</code></pre>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-subcommands">Subcommands</h4>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-import">import<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Import current deployment state for an application and generate a sync m=
anifest.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-a, --application_id</td>
<td>Application ID (format: A12345)</td>
<td>-a A12ABC</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-o, --output</td>
<td>Output file path (defaults to &lt;application_id&gt;-sync-manifest.json=
)</td>
<td>-o my-manifest.json</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-d, --deployments</td>
<td>Include deployment information: environments, swimlanes, all</td>
<td>-d all</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync import =
-a A12ABC                    # Basic import, creates a12abc-sync-manifest.j=
son
mesh sync import -a A12ABC -o manifest.json  # Custom output filename
mesh sync import -a A12ABC -d all           # Include current deployments
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-resolve">resolve<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Resolve 'latest' versions in a sync manifest to actual deployed versions=
.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-f, --file</td>
<td>Sync manifest file path or URL</td>
<td>-f manifest.json</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-o, --output</td>
<td>Output file path (defaults to &lt;input&gt;<em>resolved</em>&lt;timesta=
mp&gt;.json)</td>
<td>-o resolved.json</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-e, --environment</td>
<td>Environment to use for resolving "latest" versions (default: dev1)</td>
<td>-e sit1</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync resolve=
 -f manifest.json                    # Creates manifest_resolved_20241201_1=
20000.json
mesh sync resolve -f manifest.json -o resolved.json   # Custom output filen=
ame =20
mesh sync resolve -f manifest.json -e sit1            # Use sit1 for versio=
n resolution
mesh sync resolve -f https://example.com/manifests/deploy.json  # Resolve f=
rom URL
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-plan">plan<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Show what changes would be made by applying a sync manifest.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-f, --file</td>
<td>Sync manifest file path or URL</td>
<td>-f manifest.json</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync plan -f=
 manifest.json                                    # Show planned changes fr=
om local file
mesh sync plan -f https://example.com/manifests/deploy.json        # Show p=
lanned changes from URL
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-apply">apply<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Apply a sync manifest to deploy components to their desired state.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-f, --file</td>
<td>Sync manifest file path or URL</td>
<td>-f manifest.json</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-t, --target</td>
<td>Target environment(s) or swimlane(s) to apply (can be specified multipl=
e times). If not specified, applies to all environments and swimlanes excep=
t prod1.</td>
<td>-t dev1 -t swimlane-abc</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync apply -=
f manifest.json                           # Apply to all targets except pro=
d1
mesh sync apply -f manifest.json --target dev1             # Apply only to =
dev1 environment
mesh sync apply -f manifest.json -t dev1 -t sit1          # Apply to dev1 a=
nd sit1 environments
mesh sync apply -f manifest.json --target swimlane-abc     # Apply only to =
specific swimlane
mesh sync apply -f https://example.com/manifests/deploy.json  # Apply from =
URL
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-release">release<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Create a prod1 change request from a sync manifest for production deploy=
ment.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-f, --file</td>
<td>Sync manifest file path or URL</td>
<td>-f manifest.json</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-l, --label</td>
<td>Change request label (optional, auto-generated if not provided)</td>
<td>-l "Release v2.1.0"</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-d, --deployment-start</td>
<td>Implementation start date/time in ISO format</td>
<td>-d "2025-12-10T15:00:00Z"</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync release=
 -f manifest.json -d "2025-12-10T15:00:00Z"
# Creates change request with auto-generated label from application name an=
d releaseVersion

mesh sync release -f manifest.json -l "My Release v2.1.0" -d "2025-12-10T15=
:00:00Z"
# Creates change request with custom label

mesh sync release -f manifest.json -d "2025-12-10T15:00:00+10:00"
# Uses timezone-aware datetime (converted to UTC)

mesh sync release -f https://example.com/manifests/deploy.json -d "2025-12-=
10T15:00:00Z"
# Create change request from manifest URL
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Important Notes:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Only components with <code>deployed: true</code> for prod1 targets are =
included in the change request</li>
<li>The manifest must include <code>changeCoordinatorGroup</code> and <code=
>releaseVersion</code> in metadata (unless label is provided)</li>
<li>A confirmation prompt shows all change details before creation</li>
<li>Components are deployed in order based on their <code>priority</code> f=
ield</li>
</ul>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-validate-1">validate<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Validate a sync manifest file against the JSON schema.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-f, --file</td>
<td>Sync manifest file path or URL</td>
<td>-f manifest.json</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh sync validat=
e -f manifest.json                           # Validate local manifest file
mesh sync validate -f https://example.com/manifests/deploy.json  # Validate=
 manifest from URL
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What it validates:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>JSON/YAML structure follows the sync manifest schema</li>
<li>All required fields are present and properly formatted</li>
<li>Component types and names reference valid components</li>
<li>Target environments are valid</li>
<li>Build numbers and version formats are correct</li>
<li>Naming conventions are followed</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-workflow-examples">Workflow Examples</h4>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> All sync commands that accept manifest files (<co=
de>-f, --file</code>) support both local file paths and URLs (http/https).<=
/p>
<p><strong>Standard Deployment Workflow:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash"># 1. Import curre=
nt state for an application
mesh sync import -a A12ABC -d all

# 2. Edit the manifest to set desired deployment targets
# (manually edit a12abc-sync-manifest.json)

# 3. Resolve any "latest" versions to concrete build numbers
mesh sync resolve -f a12abc-sync-manifest.json

# 4. Preview what changes would be made
mesh sync plan -f a12abc-sync-manifest_resolved_20241201_120000.json

# 5. Apply the changes
mesh sync apply -f a12abc-sync-manifest_resolved_20241201_120000.json
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Production Release Workflow:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash"># 1. Import curre=
nt state and prepare for production
mesh sync import -a A12ABC -d all

# 2. Edit manifest to include prod1 targets and release metadata
# (manually edit a12abc-sync-manifest.json to add changeCoordinatorGroup an=
d releaseVersion)

# 3. Resolve versions and apply to lower environments first
mesh sync resolve -f a12abc-sync-manifest.json
mesh sync apply -f a12abc-sync-manifest_resolved_20241201_120000.json --tar=
get dev1,sit1,uat1,svp1

# 4. Create production change request
mesh sync release -f a12abc-sync-manifest_resolved_20241201_120000.json -d =
"2025-12-15T09:00:00Z"
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-config">config<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The config command allows you to manage persistent configuration setting=
s for mesh developer tools. Configuration is stored in <code>~/.mesh/config=
</code> as a YAML file.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-14">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh config &lt;subcommand&gt; [options]
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-show">show<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Display current configuration settings and file contents.</p>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh config show =
   # Show current configuration
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-set">set<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Set a configuration value. Values are automatically converted to appropr=
iate types (boolean, integer, or string).</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> No validation is performed on keys or values. Any=
 key can be set to any value. The system only performs basic type conversio=
n.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>key</td>
<td>Configuration key to set (any string)</td>
<td>quiet</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>value</td>
<td>Value to set (true/false/number/string)</td>
<td>true</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh config set q=
uiet true     # Enable quiet mode by default
mesh config set quiet false    # Disable quiet mode
</code></pre>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-init">init<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h5>
<p>Create a default configuration file with example settings and comments.<=
/p>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-bash" data-language=3D"bash">mesh config init =
   # Create ~/.mesh/config with defaults
</code></pre>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-configuration-options">Configuration Options</h4>
<p><strong>Important:</strong> The configuration system accepts any key-val=
ue pairs without validation. Only the following keys have defined behavior =
in the mesh tools:</p>
<p>The configuration file supports the following options:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Type</th>
<th>Default</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>quiet</td>
<td>boolean</td>
<td>false</td>
<td>Skip yes/no confirmation prompts (auto-approve with defaults)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-configuration-file-format">Configuration File Format=
</h4>
<p>The configuration file (<code>~/.mesh/config</code>) uses YAML format:</=
p>
<pre><code class=3D"language-yaml" data-language=3D"yaml"># Mesh Developer =
Tools Configuration
# Skip yes/no confirmation prompts (auto-approve with defaults)
quiet: true
</code></pre>
<h3 id=3D"user-content-connect">connect<a rel=3D"nofollow"></a></h3>
<p>The connect command opens the specified component's page in Mesh Connect=
 in your default web browser.</p>
<p>This command may be executed from within the repository corresponding to=
 the component, or the component can be selected using the --component_name=
, --component_type or --repo_uri options.</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> This command is not available for Incubator compo=
nents.</p>
<h4 id=3D"user-content-usage-15">Usage</h4>
<pre><code>mesh connect [-n &lt;component_name&gt;] [-t &lt;component_type&=
gt;] [-r &lt;repo_uri&gt;]
</code></pre>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Option</th>
<th>Description</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>-n, --component_name</td>
<td>Component Name (defaults to component checked out in current directory)=
</td>
<td>-n mesh-rbac-v2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-t, --component_type</td>
<td>Component Type (will infer from name if not provided, and prompt if amb=
iguous)</td>
<td>-t api</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-r, --repo_uri</td>
<td>Repository uri of the component (use instead of name and type if prefer=
red)</td>
<td>-r <a rel=3D"nofollow">ssh://git@bitbucket.srv.westpac.com.au/wdp/exp-d=
ream-core-v1-api.git</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>-h, --help</td>
<td>Shows the usage help message</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Additionally supports common options: <code>-v/--verbose</code> and <cod=
e>-q/--quiet</code></p>
<h5 id=3D"user-content-examples-6">EXAMPLES</h5>
<p>Open Mesh Connect for the component in the current directory:</p>
<p><code>mesh connect</code></p>
<p>Open Mesh Connect for a specific component by name and type:</p>
<p><code>mesh connect -n mesh-rbac-v2 -t api</code></p>
<p><code>mesh connect -n dream -t singlePageApplication</code></p>
<p><code>mesh connect -n reference-orchestration-v1 -t orchestration</code>=
</p>
<p>Open Mesh Connect for a component using its repository URI:</p>
<p><code>mesh connect -r ssh://git@bitbucket.srv.westpac.com.au/wdp/wdp-mes=
h-rbac-v2-api.git</code></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
<h2 id=3D"MeshDeveloperTools-MavenChecklist">Maven Checklist</h2>
<p>This checklist is to help you to check your maven setup for some common =
issues.</p>
<p>It's important to understand that the current Tomcat 9 API container wor=
ks with Java 11, and also uses specific repositories to ensure that:</p>
<ul>
<li>dependencies come from the Devops-managed Artifactory repositories for =
your external dependencies (e.g. a properly managed Maven Central mirror);<=
/li>
<li>you can include custom packages (published to the WDP Maven repository)=
; and</li>
<li>your builds&nbsp;<em>don't</em> include snapshots</li>
</ul>
<p>To check your Maven and JDK version:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">mvn -v</=
pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>Your maven version should be 3.9.9 or later, and your Java version shoul=
d be Java 21.</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">$ mvn -v
Picked up JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS: -agentpath:"C:\Windows\system32\Aternity\Java\=
JavaHookLoader.dll"=3D"C:\ProgramData\Aternity\hooks"
Apache Maven 3.9.9 (8e8579a9e76f7d015ee5ec7bfcdc97d260186937)
Maven home: C:\ProgramData\maven\apache-maven-3.9.9
Java version: 21.0.1, vendor: Red Hat, Inc., runtime: C:\ProgramData\redhat=
\java-21-openjdk-21.0.1.0.12-3.win.jdk.x86_64
Default locale: en_AU, platform encoding: UTF-8
OS name: "windows 11", version: "10.0", arch: "amd64", family: "windows"
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>To check your current Maven repositories:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">cat ~/.m=
2/settings.xml</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">$ cat ~/=
.m2/settings.xml
&lt;?xml version=3D"1.0" encoding=3D"UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;settings xsi:schemaLocation=3D"http://maven.apache.org/SETTINGS/1.0.0 h=
ttp://maven.apache.org/xsd/settings-1.0.0.xsd" xmlns=3D"http://maven.apache=
.org/SETTINGS/1.0.0"
    xmlns:xsi=3D"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"&gt;
  &lt;localRepository&gt;C:/ProgramData/maven/.m2/repository&lt;/localRepos=
itory&gt;
  &lt;mirrors&gt;
    &lt;mirror&gt;
      &lt;mirrorOf&gt;*&lt;/mirrorOf&gt;
      &lt;name&gt;westpac-group&lt;/name&gt;
      &lt;url&gt;https://artifactory.srv.westpac.com.au/artifactory/wdp-001=
_maven&lt;/url&gt; &lt;!-- IMPORTANT: See Notes below --&gt;
      &lt;id&gt;westpac-group&lt;/id&gt;
    &lt;/mirror&gt;
  &lt;/mirrors&gt;
  &lt;profiles&gt;
    &lt;profile&gt;
      &lt;repositories&gt;
        &lt;repository&gt;
          &lt;snapshots&gt;
            &lt;enabled&gt;false&lt;/enabled&gt;
          &lt;/snapshots&gt;
          &lt;id&gt;central&lt;/id&gt;
          &lt;name&gt;libs-release&lt;/name&gt;
          &lt;url&gt;https://artifactory.srv.westpac.com.au/artifactory/lib=
s-release&lt;/url&gt;
        &lt;/repository&gt;
        &lt;repository&gt;
          &lt;snapshots /&gt;
          &lt;id&gt;snapshots&lt;/id&gt;
          &lt;name&gt;libs-snapshot&lt;/name&gt;
          &lt;url&gt;https://artifactory.srv.westpac.com.au/artifactory/lib=
s-snapshot&lt;/url&gt;
        &lt;/repository&gt;
      &lt;/repositories&gt;
      &lt;pluginRepositories&gt;
        &lt;pluginRepository&gt;
          &lt;snapshots&gt;
            &lt;enabled&gt;false&lt;/enabled&gt;
          &lt;/snapshots&gt;
          &lt;id&gt;central&lt;/id&gt;
          &lt;name&gt;plugins-release&lt;/name&gt;
          &lt;url&gt;https://artifactory.srv.westpac.com.au/artifactory/plu=
gins-release&lt;/url&gt;
        &lt;/pluginRepository&gt;
        &lt;pluginRepository&gt;
          &lt;snapshots /&gt;
          &lt;id&gt;snapshots&lt;/id&gt;
          &lt;name&gt;plugins-release&lt;/name&gt;
          &lt;url&gt;https://artifactory.srv.westpac.com.au/artifactory/plu=
gins-release&lt;/url&gt;
        &lt;/pluginRepository&gt;
      &lt;/pluginRepositories&gt;
      &lt;id&gt;artifactory&lt;/id&gt;
    &lt;/profile&gt;
  &lt;/profiles&gt;
  &lt;activeProfiles&gt;
    &lt;activeProfile&gt;artifactory&lt;/activeProfile&gt;
  &lt;/activeProfiles&gt;
&lt;/settings&gt;


</pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro confluence-information-macro-not=
e"><span class=3D"aui-icon aui-icon-small aui-iconfont-warning confluence-i=
nformation-macro-icon"></span>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro-body">
<p>Because the&nbsp;<strong>westpac-group</strong> Artifactory repository i=
ncludes clashing artifacts, the API builds now use&nbsp;<strong>wdp-001_mav=
en</strong> as shown above.</p>
